<div id="review_3385053189" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3385053189" />
    <a title="Greta" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111566858-greta"><img alt="Greta" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586844759p2/111566858.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3385053189?book_show_action=true">Jun 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greta" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greta" href="/user/show/111566858-greta">Greta</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/30631926-the-radium-girls">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111566858-greta?shelf=best-reviews">best-reviews</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111566858-greta?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3385053189" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13548464498697816342"><b>Still Glowing in Their Coffins</b><br/><br/><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1594904428i/29823622._SX540_.jpg' width='500' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><i>Factory women painting radium containing paint on whatches, so that they would glow in the dark </i><br/><br/>What do you think about, when you hear radiation poisoning?<br/>Probably the death of Marie Curie, the atom bombs and Chernobyl. But the story of the &quot;Radium girls&quot;, as they were called by the media, was just as bad and happened even earlier.<br/><br/>Meant are the female factory workers who contracted radiation poisoning from painting watch dials with self-luminous and radium containin</span>
  <span id="freeText13548464498697816342" style="display:none"><b>Still Glowing in Their Coffins</b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1594904428i/29823622._SX540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Factory women painting radium containing paint on whatches, so that they would glow in the dark </i><br><br>What do you think about, when you hear radiation poisoning?<br>Probably the death of Marie Curie, the atom bombs and Chernobyl. But the story of the "Radium girls", as they were called by the media, was just as bad and happened even earlier.<br><br>Meant are the female factory workers who contracted radiation poisoning from painting watch dials with self-luminous and radium containing painting in three different factories in the United States, starting in 1917. The woman ingested deadly amounts of radium when pointing their brushes on their lips to give them a fine tip, which was something they did hundreds of times each day.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1594908805i/29824561._SY540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Charlotte Purcell, one of the radium girls, demonstrates the lip-pointing technique that they used to get the brushes to a fine point. They amputated her left arm due to radiation poisining</i><br><br>Of course many women developed severe sickness and died. The factories recognized that, but didn’t intervene. Instead they even tried to cover everything up. Alone in 1920 four million watches were produced and more than one hundred women died. This story focuses on four of those women, who took legal action and sued their factory, instating a precedent for workers rights and safety standards, that impact employees rights until today. One of the woman died during the process, the others briefly after. You are introduced to their characters, their health stories and go along with them through the trial. They were called the “living deaths”.<br><br><b>The medicine in the story </b><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1594906528i/29823873._SX540_.png" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Grace Fryer with the "radium jaw" a.k.a. phossy jaw - the first woman that decided to sue.</i><br><br>It was horrible to read how those woman were let down by doctors. They had devastating symptoms, causing them severe pain and disfiguring them, from loosing teeth and removed jaws to amputations. Their doctors didn’t knew what was wrong, came up with wrong diagnosis and made a lot of money in the process. Some of them turned out to be frauds and were bribed. As the woman expressed their suspicion that their symptoms were work related, pathologist conspired with factories to state syphilis as cause of death, depriving the women of their social standing and their credibility. <br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1594907206i/29824104._SX540_.jpg" width="500" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Radium poisoning affected all areas of the body and many of the radium girls quickly couldn‘t walk anymore and had amputations </i><br><br>They glowed in the dark and rotted from within, but it took a long time for the first doctor to identify radiation as cause. The women didn’t have health insurance and paid for every visit and treatment, depriving them of all their savings. Once the doctors knew the cause and that they didn’t have a cure but that it was deadly, they didn’t tell the patient! They kept from the women that they had a death sentence, often until the very end. Catherine Donohue wasn‘t told that she had only days or weeks to live, until her doctor had to testify in court under oath, causing her to have a nervous breakdown. After the effects of radium were revealed, many former factory workers developed severe mental issues from the knowledge that they were deadly poisoned, even if they didn‘t show any symptoms yet.<br><br><b>The verdict </b><br><br> <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1594906063i/29823827._SX540_.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><i>Catherine Donohue, one of the radium girls, died during the process </i><br><br>It took the women two years to even find a lawyer who was willing to represent them. No one else wanted to take on a factory, they were just interested in money, which the women didn’t have. That is why the media played an extremely important role in that verdict. The women chose to go public and people started to protest in their favor and against the exploitation of workers. The factories appealed until they reached the Supreme Court but lost, so that they had to pay compensations and future health bills. The verdict had a major impact on work politics and guaranteed safety standards for employees all through America. When the Second World War emerged they applied the same security standards to those in contact with plutonium as well, probably saving countless lives.<br><br><i>"The cynical would say there was only one reason a high-profile specialist finally took up the cause. On June 7, 1925, the first male employee of the United States Radium Corporation died.” </i><br><br>This book is very nicely written - very much like a novel. Because it combines my interests of law, medicine and history it‘s absolutely among my favorite non-fiction books.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13548464498697816342" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


