    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2233588565" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2233588565" />
    <a title="Monica" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4739465-monica"><img alt="Monica" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577896647p2/4739465.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2233588565?book_show_action=true">Apr 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Monica" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Monica" href="/user/show/4739465-monica">Monica</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/34394482-the-radium-girls">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=female-author-nonfic">female-author-nonfic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=wh_fem_nonfic">wh_fem_nonfic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=pub_2010s">pub_2010s</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=soc-sci-politics">soc-sci-politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=kindle_nonfiction">kindle_nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=science-human-anatomy-behaviors">science-human-anatomy-behaviors</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=women-savvy">women-savvy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=popular">popular</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4739465-monica?shelf=science">science</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2233588565" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7511438964575254109">Radium Girls was a horrific example of how corporations put profits over people and how they are enabled by the local and governing authorities who were in effect purchased by the wealthy corporations. It heavily indicts the very wealthy settling once and for all the idea that they really don&apos;t care about workers. In this instance they exploited poor, uneducated, young, white women, which is somehow, not the least bit surprising. As we all wait amid the COVID 19 pandemic, I can&apos;t help but see th</span>
  <span id="freeText7511438964575254109" style="display:none">Radium Girls was a horrific example of how corporations put profits over people and how they are enabled by the local and governing authorities who were in effect purchased by the wealthy corporations. It heavily indicts the very wealthy settling once and for all the idea that they really don't care about workers. In this instance they exploited poor, uneducated, young, white women, which is somehow, not the least bit surprising. As we all wait amid the COVID 19 pandemic, I can't help but see this book through a lens that was never intended.<br /><br />This book is infuriating on a human level. When examined from 21st century eyes it's pretty stunning how callous and amoral white males can be. Not just the corporation, but the scientists, the doctors, the lawyers, the government agencies, the media etc. It's just so surprising…not. I suppose what is also gulling is the notion that everything in this book is completely believable. Not one of the awful things that happened in this book struck me as hyperbolized or outlandish. More like human nature. Greed. Hubris. Misogyny. The Economy.<br /><br />Fast forward literally one hundred years and the notion that it would be a job requirement to put paint in the mouth <i>"lip, dip, paint"</i>, let alone radium tinted paint is just ludicrous. Any job that requires employees to put something in their mouth that is not food or potable liquid…well I'd like to think it just couldn't happen today. Of course I didn't live in that era (these women could've been my great grandparents), I'm not a teenager, and I'm not white. That last point is huge. You'd never know by this book that "Negroes" existed in the 1920s. One could extrapolate that the United States Radium Corporation and the Radium and Luminous Materials Corporation (aka corporations that dealt in luminous paint and other radioactive materials) didn't hire Negroes. Not unexpected, it's the 1920s after all. These jobs were considered very prestigious. One of the few times in history where Jim Crow probably saved lives. Thank goodness that Kate Moore revived this time in history. Because of these women's suffering and sacrifice; corporations today cannot take advantage of their workers preferring profits to the determent of actual people…oh wait… It seems that almost 100 years later, America has done a really good job of forgetting. In 2012 Mitt Romney, a presidential candidate for the Republican party declares that "Corporations are people, my friend". In 2016, 53% of voting white women voted for and handed the presidency to a man whose administration has deliberately catered to corporations at the expense of workers, gutted the EPA, CDC, sabotaged labor relations, weakened labor unions, weakened health care laws, weakened industrial safety laws, and has a law enforcement arm (Department of Justice) that is reviled nationally and worldwide. And in 2020 amid a global pandemic, this same government has suggested that senior citizens (a very high risk group for fatalities) should be willing to die so that the economy such as it is can keep chugging along. The history of suffering and sacrifice that those women endured only to have their legacy forgotten and their heirs, working hard by voting against their self interest to remove the gains of the past. Voting in politicians that openly campaign against government oversight, immigration programs, environmental standards, organized labor, racial and gender equality, and corporate taxation. As if being white (and female) shields them from effects of the horrors that selfishness, lack of compassion, inhumanity and systemic inequality. Gaslighted. I see it as all related. Why were these women so dutifully willing to do such a foolish thing? Cultural indoctrination? Stockholm syndrome? That same question applies to 100 years ago as well as 3 years ago. And to dismiss or allow history to fade so that they can do it all again and include all poor people, not just poor white women though they too are singled out in this current era (teachers unions in TX, WV, OK, KY ect). As long as the boards of directors and the leadership in the government are not diverse, this kind of callous disregard for the effects of policy and process on people of all backgrounds; the system will never be fair and no one is safe.<br /><br />The postscript was especially chilling. It describes the firm Luminous Processes had just shut down in 1978 with it's facilities registering 1,666 times higher than is considered safe levels of radiation. This company was located in Ottawa, IL one of the original locations in the story. The workers noted all kinds of unsafe practices before the closure. The workers complained of tumors and a high rate of breast cancer prior to the closing. I would note that the author stayed away from describing the workers in the postscript. Certainly not the way she was described each of the original radium girls. I can't help but wonder if by 1978, the average Luminous Processes worker had a much higher population of people of color. That would for me have been an interesting exploration. I wonder if the white women's history was passed along in the families and they shied away from the employment with radium/radioactive material corporations? Were there any descendants of the Radium girls still working at that firm by 1978?<br /><br />The book was fascinating and infuriating. For me too many of the girls had similar stories that had no major impact on the storyline. I understand the desire to honor the legacy of these women. I think Moore spent more time telling the story than analyzing the effects . For me the book would have benefitted by examining what has happened in terms of occupational safety since these proceedings. I would've liked the post script to have been part of the book and much longer and more substantive. I suppose that would not have been the tribute that Moore intended to write. A good book that highlights the tragedy and lessons of unregulated commerce and capitalism. Where the corporations were allowed to prey upon poor, uneducated, young, workers. As the postscript shows, those who haven't learned the lessons of history are doomed to repeat it. A very well written and important, though unnecessarily narrow slice of history.<br /><br /><i>4 Stars</i><br /><br />Read on kindle</span>
  <a data-text-id="7511438964575254109" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


